 :tx/rationale "C9 PROPOSAL: Parameter Substrate Independence — if two projects using the same kernel would want different values for a constant, that constant is policy, not kernel. C8 says 'don't hardcode domain-specific logic.' C9 says 'don't hardcode domain-specific values.' Same principle, different abstraction level. C8 catches functions that assume Go/Rust/React. C9 catches constants that assume a specific project size, domain vocabulary, or observation density. THE LITMUS TEST: 'Would a React project, a research lab, and a compliance team all want this exact value?' If no, it's a policy datom. If yes (like f32 epsilon or max u64), it's a kernel constant. EXAMPLES: JOIN_THRESHOLD (0.20) — fails C9 (different embedding models, different domains). MIN_CLUSTER_SIZE (3) — fails C9 (a solo researcher might want 2, a large team might want 5). DEFAULT_DIM (256) — passes C9 (model-specific, not domain-specific, and the model IS fixed). l2_normalize epsilon (1e-10) — passes C9 (numerical stability, universal). This completes the constraint hierarchy: C1-C7 (data invariants), C8 (logic substrate independence), C9 (parameter substrate independence)."
